Here's a minimal API endpoint handling multipart form uploads with multiple images and a description:

```csharp
// Program.cs

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size (default is ~30MB)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o => o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 50 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    var form = await request.ReadFormAsync(new FormOptions
    {
        MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 50 * 1024 * 1024
    });

    var description = form["description"].ToString();
    var files = form.Files.GetFiles("images");

    if (files.Count == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No images provided.");

    var saved = new List<string>();

    foreach (var file in files)
    {
        if (!file.ContentType.StartsWith("image/"))
            return Results.BadRequest($"'{file.FileName}' is not an image.");

        var dest = Path.Combine("uploads", $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}");
        Directory.CreateDirectory("uploads");

        await using var stream = File.Create(dest);
        await file.CopyToAsync(stream);
        saved.Add(dest);
    }

    return Results.Ok(new { description, fileCount = saved.Count, paths = saved });
})
.DisableAntiforgery();          // required for minimal APIs accepting forms without AF tokens

app.Run();
```

**Key pieces:**

| Concern | What handles it |
|---|---|
| 50 MB limit | `KestrelServerOptions.MaxRequestBodySize` **and** `FormOptions.MultipartBodyLengthLimit` — both must be raised |
| Multiple files | `form.Files.GetFiles("images")` matches the form field name |
| Text field | `form["description"]` reads the plain string part |
| Antiforgery | `.DisableAntiforgery()` opts out (needed unless you wire up AF tokens) |

**Example `curl` to test:**

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/upload \
  -F "description=Vacation photos" \
  -F "images=@photo1.jpg" \
  -F "images=@photo2.png"
```

If you prefer model binding over manual form reading, you can use a typed approach instead:

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload-typed", async (
    [FromForm] string description,
    [FromForm] IFormFileCollection images) =>
{
    // same processing logic as above
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```
